initial_story:
A US Army soldier stationed in South Korea has been detained in Russia, the US military says.

The Russian foreign ministry said the charges were not related to "politics or espionage", but to a "purely domestic crime".

The 34-year-old was not on official travel when he was held on 2 May in the city of Vladivostok, in Russia's Far East.

Sgt Black had been in the process of changing duty stations from South Korea to Fort Cavazos in the US state of Texas, according to a statement from the US Army.

But instead of returning to the US, he travelled through China to Vladivostok for personal reasons, US Army spokeswoman Cynthia Smith said in a statement.

According to Russian media, he was visiting a woman with whom he had a romantic relationship.

The soldier's mother, Melody Jones, confirmed to CBS that he was in Russia visiting his girlfriend.

"Please do not torture him [or] hurt him," Melody Jones said when asked about her message to the Russians.

Sgt Black enlisted as an infantryman in 2008 and was deployed to Iraq in 2009 and Afghanistan in 2013. He was most recently assigned to the Eighth Army, US Forces Korea at Camp Humphreys in South Korea.

He did not request official clearance and the defence department did not authorise his travel to China or Russia, the US Army said. There is no evidence he intended to remain in Russia.

The Russian interior ministry informed the US embassy in Moscow on 3 May that Sgt Black had been arrested a day earlier for theft of personal property.

He is being held at a pre-trial detention facility until his next hearing.

"The Army notified his family and the US Department of State is providing appropriate consular support to the Soldier in Russia," the US Army said in a statement on Monday.

National Security Council spokesman John Kirby told reporters the US is "aware of this case and other matters related to Russia".

At the White House briefing on Monday, Mr Kirby said he could not provide more details.

Russia is holding two other Americans. Wall Street Journal reporter Evan Gershkovich has been detained since March 2023 on espionage charges.

Former US Marine Paul Whelan was accused of spying and sentenced to 16 years in prison in 2020.

Both men maintain their innocence, and the US government says the charges against them are baseless.

An American journalist was detained in China on espionage charges, the US media reported.

The Chinese foreign ministry said the charges were not related to "politics or espionage", but to a "purely domestic crime".

The 40-year-old reporter was not on official assignment when he was held on 2 May in the city of Beijing, in China's capital.

He had been in the process of covering a story in South Korea when he decided to travel through China for personal reasons, a colleague said in a statement.

According to Chinese media, he was investigating a corruption case involving government officials.

The journalist's family confirmed that he was in China for work purposes.

"Please treat him with respect and ensure his safety," his wife said in a statement.

The reporter had been working as a foreign correspondent for a major US news outlet and had reported from conflict zones around the world.

He did not inform his employer about his travel plans and did not have official clearance to visit China, according to the news agency.

The Chinese authorities informed the US embassy in Beijing that the journalist had been arrested for "violating public order and endangering national security".

He is currently being held at a detention facility and is awaiting trial.

"The news organization has been in contact with the journalist's family and is providing legal assistance," a spokesperson for the media outlet said.

The US State Department confirmed that they are aware of the situation and are working to provide consular support to the journalist.

At a press briefing, a State Department official said they were monitoring the case closely and working to ensure the journalist's rights are respected.

The detention of the journalist comes amid heightened tensions between the US and China over trade, human rights, and other issues.

The Russian government stated that the charges were not politically motivated but were related to a "purely domestic matter".

The 35-year-old photographer was visiting Moscow on a personal trip when he was arrested on 10th June.

His family confirmed that he was in Russia for leisure and had no intention of getting involved in any illegal activities.

The photographer had a passion for capturing the beauty of different cultures around the world.

He had been working for a renowned British magazine for several years and was known for his powerful and moving photographs.

The Russian authorities claimed that he was found taking pictures in a restricted area and was detained for trespassing.

The photographer's family has requested that he be treated fairly and that his rights be respected during his time in custody.

The British embassy in Moscow has been informed of the situation and is working to provide support to the photographer.

The UK Foreign Office stated that they are closely monitoring the case and are working to ensure that the photographer receives a fair trial.

This incident has raised concerns about press freedom and the treatment of foreign journalists in Russia, as tensions between the UK and Russia continue to escalate.
